thread.title: UA basketball begins practice with roles to be filled

author: azcentral.com
title: UA basketball begins practice with roles to be filled
text:
TUCSON – If Sean Miller is smart, and if there is enough money left in the till, he should see if Michael Buffer is available for each and every of Arizona’s preseason practices.
“Let’s get ready to rumble!” he would scream in his inimitable style, because that is exactly what the next four weeks will be for the Wildcats.
A rumble of the highest order – “a royal rumble,” in fact, Gabe York says – a no-holds-barred battle of basketball bravado. Last man standing.
Scratch that: Last four men standing.
AZCENTRAL
Five-star prospect T.J. Leaf decommits from Arizona Wildcats
Unlike recent history, Arizona enters its season searching for much more than The Man. Nick or Aaron, T.J. or Stanley – who cares, they won 67 games over two years.
This year is different. Spots are being fought for, war is being waged.
Gone are McConnell and Johnson, Rondae Hollis-Jefferson and Brandon Ashley. Here are Kadeem Allen and Elliott Pitts and Justin Simon and Ray Smith and Allonzo Trier … we can keep going.
Instead, let the games begin.
AZCENTRAL
Arizona Wildcats XTRA app: Get latest news, scores
“Everyone gets thrown into the fire,” said York, who along with guys like Kaleb Tarczewski, Mark Tollefsen and Ryan Anderson, has the benefit of game experience. “Whoever comes out alive will be the starters.”
Let’s not go that far.
OK, let’s.
“We compete with each other like no other – if it’s to fistfights, bloody noses, we just want to compete and bring the best out of each other,” Allen said.
Kaleb Tarczewski on not apologizing for being a four-year player Paola Boivin
So maybe not “whoever comes out alive,” but it’s still going to be pretty tough this year. Because the stakes are raised for the second unit. Arizona might not have 35-minute men to rely on. Entering the season, guys up and down the lineup feel like they have something to prove, something to earn.
“The last two years, guys were still competing every day and going at each other and fighting for minutes – that’s the case with every college team, because guys want to play – but this year, minutes are going to be closer,” Pitts said.
“It’s definitely a different dynamic than in year’s past,” Tarczewski added. “We’ve kind of always known what we’re gonna get going into the season. This year I’d say this is not the case. Even with some of the guys returning, we don’t know what we’re going to get.”
They know they’re not going to get Johnson’s 13.8 points or Ashley’s .514 shooting percentage. McConnell’s 6.3 assists? Adios. Hollis-Jefferson’s 6.8 rebounds and approximately 8.41 shimmies per game? So long and sayonara.
AZCENTRAL
Arizona basketball: Eyes of Sean Miller upon Texas for recruits
“You look at that core – they’ve done a lot a damage in terms of us winning over the last two years,” Miller said. “We knew this time was coming, and even with our recruiting efforts of bringing in what I think will be a solid class for us, eventually there’s a drop off. It can certainly be negated by experience … we’ve tried to bridge the gap with experience and doing it today’s way.”
Gone perhaps is the buffer of the years past, that breathing room that comes along with so much returning talent.
In its place this season, maybe a new one. Even louder than the other.
One thing is for sure. The Wildcats are ready to rumble.
